Interestingly enough, sometimes the finest examples of French Cognac can be found more readily in Britain than in their country of origin. Perhaps this is because the Brit-

z ne ish are a patient people who are willing to wait, or perhaps it is because of the moist climate which affects the maturing in a very special way. Whatever the cause, we want to state that this little lot, available only in the smallest non-commercial quantity, has more breed, more delicacy, and a more distinguished bouquet than many Brandies that sell for twice the price. Back in 1936, the fine old Cognac firm of Augier Freres made this small shipment to Britain where it has been stored, untouched, in oak casks for 20 years.
